    <h1>Dig&#xAD;i&#xAD;tal&#xAD;is&#xAD;ing data blocks in the sup&#xAD;ply chain</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201215/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-15"><time>2020-12-15</time></a>
        - <span>TECH</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Dig­i­tal tools that en­gen­der trust in food, medicine and vaccine prove­nance will at­tract Singapore’s key re­search funds from 2021 to 2025.</p>
    <p>The Na­tional Re­search Foun­da­tion’s (NRF) newly an­nounced $25 bil­lion fund will also cover ef­forts to com­mer­cialise th­ese tech­nolo­gies over the next five years to se­cure Singapore’s dig­i­tal lead­er­ship.</p>
    <p>In an­nounc­ing the fund last Fri­day, Deputy Prime Min­is­ter Heng Swee Keat said: “In a post-Covid world where re­silience is pri­ori­tised, Singapore can... de­velop ‘trust mark’ so­lu­tions to cer­tify prod­ucts for ex­port in crit­i­cal sec­tors such as food and healthcare.”</p>
    <p>Mr Heng, who is also Fi­nance Min­is­ter and chair­man of the NRF, cited blockchain tech­nol­ogy as an ex­am­ple of such a so­lu­tion.</p>
    <p>Although it was ini­tially cre­ated to en­able cryp­tocur­rency, the tech­nol­ogy is also in­creas­ingly be­ing used by busi­nesses and govern­ments to en­sure au­then­tic­ity and trans­parency in record keep­ing.</p>
    <p>At Pasir Pan­jang Whole­sale Cen­tre, for in­stance, some fruit and pro­duce on sale al­ready bear stick­ers with QR codes that link to in­for­ma­tion re­gard­ing their ori­gin, pack­ing lo­ca­tion and prod­uct cer­tifi­cate.</p>
    <p>DiMuto, a Singapore-based blockchain start-up, is be­hind th­ese QR codes and the dig­i­tal­i­sa­tion of the sup­ply chain of some traders at the mar­ket.</p>
    <p>Blockchain­s in­volve the use of de­cen­tralised dig­i­tal data­bases con­tain­ing in­for­ma­tion about trans­ac­tions or con­tracts that is un­al­ter­able and vis­i­ble to all in the chain.</p>
    <p>Mr Gary Loh, chief ex­ec­u­tive of­fi­cer and founder of DiMuto, said: “With the im­mutabil­ity of the blockchain, sup­ply chain part­ners can now have shared cus­tody of (the) truth and know ex­actly what is hap­pen­ing on the ground be­yond their own (part) in the sup­ply chain.”</p>
    <p>Cur­rently, pa­per-based records make it nearly im­pos­si­ble to trace prod­ucts from end to end.</p>
    <p>With blockchain ap­pli­ca­tion, it is hoped that fraud will be re­duced and dis­putes will be eas­ily re­solved when buy­ers raise qual­ity com­plaints.</p>
    <p>Be­sides trac­ing f ood sup­ply from farm to ta­ble, blockchain tech­nolo­gies can also track the sup­ply and trans­porta­tion of medicine, in­clud­ing vac­cines – which are cru­cial now that Covid-19 vac­cines are be­ing read­ied for dis­tri­bu­tion.</p>
    <p>An­other ap­pli­ca­tion area is in ver­i­fi­ca­tion of the his­tory of sec­ond-hand cars.</p>
    <p>“Trust tech­nolo­gies will en­able Singapore to carve out a unique niche,” Mr Heng said last week.</p>
    <p>Over the next three years, NRF will fund a $12 mil­lion pro­gramme to sup­port the devel­op­ment and com­mer­cial­i­sa­tion of real-world ap­pli­ca­tions for blockchain.</p>
    <p>The pro­gramme is a joint ef­fort with En­ter­prise Singapore and the In­fo­comm Me­dia Devel­op­ment Au­thor­ity.</p>
    <p>Their ini­tial fo­cus will be on ap</p>
    <p>Be­sides trac­ing food sup­ply from farm to ta­ble, blockchain tech­nolo­gies can also track the sup­ply and trans­porta­tion of medicine, in­clud­ing vac­cines – which are cru­cial now that Covid-19 vac­cines are be­ing read­ied for dis­tri­bu­tion. An­other ap­pli­ca­tion area is in ver­i­fi­ca­tion of the his­tory of sec­ond-hand cars.</p>
    <p>ply­ing the tech­nol­ogy in the trade and lo­gis­tics sec­tor.</p>
    <p>Last Fri­day, Min­is­ter for Com­mu­ni­ca­tions and In­for­ma­tion S. Iswaran said: “Over time, our hope is that Singapore will have the ca­pa­bil­i­ties... in trust-re­lated tech­nolo­gies, so that th­ese can be ap­plied across the econ­omy.”</p>
    <p>Irene Tham</p>

